The Day Software Became the Boss: A Real Story from India‚Äôs Tech Revolution
Divyansh Joshi
Divyansh Joshi

Following
4 min read
¬∑
Jul 3, 2025





Press enter or click to view image in full size

GEMINI
üí° Note: AI tools were used to clean up formatting and help rewrite some sections of this post for better clarity. The core idea, voice, and perspective are mine.

When people think of Artificial Intelligence in India, they usually imagine facial recognition in airports, chat bots on e-commerce apps, or maybe some startup in Bengaluru building models for stock market prediction. But the real revolution may not come from startups or research labs.

It might begin behind a busy dosa counter.

Can AI Replace the Local Manager?
Let‚Äôs take a scenario. You walk into a modest South Indian caf√© near Nagpur ‚Äî steel tumblers, sambar spills, waiters shouting over the noise. Except, in this caf√©, there‚Äôs no manager barking orders. Instead, each staff member wears a basic Bluetooth headset. An invisible AI system quietly guides them:

‚ÄúClean table four.‚Äù
‚ÄúPrepare two masala dosas.‚Äù
‚ÄúCheck the restroom every 45 minutes.‚Äù

This AI, nicknamed Saarthi, doesn‚Äôt need fancy hardware or cloud GPUs. It‚Äôs a simple local system that reads inputs like order flow, cleanliness status, and time-of-day patterns. It dispatches tasks, tracks completion, and ensures smooth operations ‚Äî all without human supervision.

The result?

Staff are more efficient.
Customers are happier.
The business saves money.
And most interestingly, no one misses the manager.

Why This Matters
What makes this scenario powerful isn‚Äôt the technology. It‚Äôs the context. This isn‚Äôt a multinational chain automating its back-end. It‚Äôs a humble caf√© ‚Äî the kind where plastic chairs wobble, but chai hits differently. And that‚Äôs where the potential of AI in India lies.

AI is no longer limited to labs and LLMs. It‚Äôs entering the informal economy. Quietly. Efficiently.

Saarthi is just one example of a broader movement: using AI not to replace workers, but to organize them better.

Press enter or click to view image in full size

Courtesy of ChatGPT
üß† Other Everyday Applications of AI Emerging in India
1. AI-Powered Kirana Inventory Management
Small grocery shops across India often rely on intuition to restock. But tools are now emerging that:

Track best-selling SKUs
Predict demand based on festivals, weather, or cricket matches
Auto-generate supplier lists via WhatsApp
Think of it as a mini BigBasket brain for your corner kirana.

2. Voice-First AI for Farmers
Instead of English-only apps, several initiatives are building AI tools in Hindi, Marathi, Bengali ‚Äî accessible via phone call. A farmer can ask:

‚ÄúWhat pesticide for leaf curl in tomatoes?‚Äù
‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs today‚Äôs mandi rate for onions?‚Äù
And get voice responses instantly, powered by domain-specific AI.
3. Smart Waste Management
In cities like Indore and Surat, AI is can be used to:

Detect overflowing garbage bins via image analysis
Optimize garbage truck routes based on sensor data
Identify littering hotspots
It‚Äôs like Swachh Bharat meets Silicon Valley.

4. Automated School Attendance & Alerts
Low-cost facial recognition or QR systems can help teachers in rural schools:

Mark attendance with a click
Send SMS alerts to parents
Detect drop-out patterns using basic analytics
5. Digital Assistants for Rural Healthcare Workers
ASHA and ANM workers can now use voice-input AI tools to:

Log patient vitals
Get medicine reminders
Detect risk factors like malnutrition using data models
They don‚Äôt need to be tech-savvy. They just need to speak.

But‚Ä¶ Is This the Future We Want?
These examples raise critical questions ‚Äî especially for us in Computer Science:

Are we building systems that assist, or systems that control?
Will AI empower workers, or turn them into step-following bots?
Who decides the logic? Who audits the ethics?
In the case of Saarthi, workers appreciated not being yelled at, and tasks became easier. But the silence ‚Äî the total absence of human feedback ‚Äî can also feel strange. When you‚Äôre told what to do every minute, at what point do you stop thinking?

The Invisible Revolution
India‚Äôs AI moment won‚Äôt look like Silicon Valley. It‚Äôll be messier, cheaper, and more frugal. It will happen in languages that global AI companies don‚Äôt support. It will run on second-hand PCs and phones. And it will change how work happens across caf√©s, kiranas, classrooms, and clinics.

Not with robots.

But with quiet, invisible software.

If you‚Äôre building in AI today, don‚Äôt just look at autonomous cars or generative models. Look at the chaiwala. The ASHA worker. The street vendor. That‚Äôs where AI can be truly transformational.

Not just artificial intelligence. But applied intelligence





