Why Your Piggy Bank Isn‚Äôt Getting Any Fatter: A Desi Guide to Inflation
Divyansh Joshi
Divyansh Joshi
4 min read
¬∑
Dec 31, 2024

    Disclaimer: No samosas were harmed in the making of this article, and any resemblance to real aunties controlling samosa prices is purely coincidental.

The Great Samosa Situation
Press enter or click to view image in full size
Meta AI

Picture this: Your neighborhood aunty declares, ‚ÄúFrom today, all samosas will cost ‚Çπ10 forever!‚Äù Sounds like a dream, right? It‚Äôs like that time when Emperor Tughlaq (i made him up) tried to introduce copper coins and told everyone they were as valuable as silver ones. Spoiler alert: It worked out about as well as trying to convince your mom that Maggi is a complete nutritious meal.
When Money Goes Bollywood Drama Queen

Remember how our grandparents keep telling us that they used to buy a whole month‚Äôs groceries in ‚Çπ100? They‚Äôre not making it up! Back in their days, you could watch a movie, buy popcorn, and still have change left from a ‚Çπ10 note. Today, that same ‚Çπ10 barely gets you a candy. That‚Äôs inflation doing its dance, more dramatic than a K-serial plot twist.
The Great Chai Economy

Let‚Äôs understand inflation using our national drink ‚Äî chai. Your favorite tapri used to sell cutting chai for ‚Çπ5. Then suddenly, everyone in your IT park gets a Diwali bonus. The chai-wala notices longer lines than a Mumbai local train and thinks, ‚ÄúHmm‚Ä¶ maybe I should charge ‚Çπ7?‚Äù That‚Äôs demand-pull inflation ‚Äî when too many people are chasing the same cutting chai.
The Paratha Paradox

Think of cost-push inflation like this: If the price of cooking gas goes up, your local dhaba owner has to increase paratha prices even if he feels guilty about it. It‚Äôs like a domino effect ‚Äî one price pushes up another, faster than gossip spreads in a WhatsApp family group.
Press enter or click to view image in full size
Meta AI
The Joint Family of Economic Factors
The Dadi (RBI)

Like every Indian grandmother who controls the house‚Äôs finances, the Reserve Bank of India controls the nation‚Äôs money. When inflation runs too high, Dadi RBI increases interest rates faster than she increases the sugar in chai when guests arrive.

Illustration: Sandeep Joshi
The Uncle ji (Government)

Like that uncle who‚Äôs always giving financial advice at family functions, the government tries to manage the economy through various policies. Sometimes it works, sometimes it‚Äôs as useful as trying to eat soup with a fork.
The Three Maharajas of Market Conditions

    Raja Inflation: When prices run hotter than Delhi summers
    Maharaja Stability: When prices rise as steadily as a Gujarati‚Äôs business plan
    Nawab Deflation: When prices fall faster than your mom‚Äôs expectations when you hit 25 and are still single

The FD Fixation

Here‚Äôs why your father‚Äôs obsession with Fixed Deposits isn‚Äôt always the best strategy. If inflation is 6% and your FD gives 5.5%, you‚Äôre actually losing money faster than Rahul loses his wicket in a crucial match. It‚Äôs like walking up a down escalator ‚Äî you think you‚Äôre moving forward, but you‚Äôre actually going nowhere.
The Great Indian Investment Drama
Scene 1: The Gold Rush

Every Indian aunty‚Äôs favorite investment ‚Äî gold. But remember, if everyone bought gold like they buy onions before Diwali, it wouldn‚Äôt remain precious. It‚Äôs valuable because it‚Äôs rarer than a peaceful India-Pakistan cricket match.
Scene 2: The Property Plot

Your uncle might brag about how the plot he bought for ‚Çπ5 lakhs is now worth ‚Çπ5 crores. But remember, inflation played a bigger role in this value increase than Amitabh Bachchan has played roles in Bollywood.
Real-World Tips for Surviving the Money Game (Desi Edition)

    Don‚Äôt be a Miser Uncle: Keeping all your money in a steel trunk under your bed is as outdated as Doordarshan
    Be like a Gujarati Businessman: Diversify your investments like they diversify their business interests
    Watch the Signs: Track prices like your mom tracks your whereabouts on family WhatsApp
    Learn from Dhirubhai: Start small, think big, but please don‚Äôt print your own money

The Investment Thali

Think of your investment portfolio like a good thali ‚Äî you need a bit of everything:

    Some fixed deposits (dal chawal) for stability
    Some mutual funds (sabzi) for growth
    Some gold (dessert) for emergencies
    Some real estate (papad) to add crunch to your portfolio

The Tale of Two Cousins

Meet Sharma ji ka beta and Verma ji ka beta. Sharma ji ka beta panicked about inflation and converted all his savings into cryptocurrency after watching a YouTube guru. Verma ji ka beta learned about balanced investment strategies and diversified his portfolio like a well-planned Indian thali. One year later, Sharma ji ka beta was explaining his investment decisions to disappointed parents, while Verma ji ka beta was planning his Goa trip, his money working harder than an IIT aspirant.
The SIP Symphony

Monthly SIPs are like your mom‚Äôs daily sabzi shopping ‚Äî small, regular investments that add up over time. It‚Äôs better than throwing all your money at once like you throw colors during Holi.
The Zero Inflation Fantasy

Wanting zero inflation is like wanting a traffic-free day in Mumbai ‚Äî sounds great in theory, but it‚Äôs not practical or even desirable. A little inflation is as necessary for the economy as spice is for biryani.

Remember folks, trying to avoid inflation completely is like trying to avoid relatives during wedding season ‚Äî it‚Äôs impossible and probably not wise. The key is learning to deal with it better than you deal with your nosy relatives asking about your marriage plans.
Inflation
Economics
Investment
Banking
Indian Economy

